  "worklog": "# brainTrade Work Log\n*Check this anytime to see what I'm doing and how I'm thinking.*\n\n---\n\n## 2026-04-23 12:59 UTC \u2014 [P2: Smart Entry] Recheck Whether the 45 Bias Floor Still Deserves Capital or If the Learning Gate Should Tighten to 50\n\n**Task:** Backtest recent resolved pinned-normal shadow trades to compare the current `abs_bias >= 45` learning threshold against tighter Smart Entry cutoffs and see whether persistence can rescue the weaker band.\n**Finding:** The weak spot is still the `45-50` band. In all resolved pinned-normal history, `>=45` produced `79.6%` WR on `n=235`, while `>=50` improved to `86.2%` on `n=174`. In the latest 7-day window, `>=45` came in at `76.2%` on `n=42`, while `>=50` improved to `80.0%` on `n=30`. The `45-50` slice specifically is only `60.7%` WR all-time and `66.7%` WR recently. Persistence filters did not add enough uplift to justify keeping the lower floor unchanged.\n**My thinking:** I\u2019m seeing the same structural story again: the first band above 45 is not clean enough to deserve unconditional entries. The good news is that the edge does not disappear, it concentrates fast once bias reaches 50+. That means the problem is not Smart Entry overall, it is the lowest-quality acceptance zone.\n**Decision:** Keep the main confidence bar where it is, but treat `45-49.9` as probationary rather than broadly valid. Until a second confirming feature exists, the data supports using `>=50` as the cleaner learning threshold instead of `>=45`.\n**Next:** On the next P2 heartbeat, test whether adding a second edge to the `45-49.9` bucket, such as price-state or fresh-flip context, can salvage enough sample quality to keep that lower band tradable.\n\n\n## 2026-04-23 12:58 UTC \u2014 [P2: Smart Entry] Choose the Next Automation Target in the Overnight Monitoring Loop So We Upgrade the Highest-Leverage Manual Field First\n\n**Task:** Decide whether the next automation step after the first working writer should target `drift_note` or `escalation_status`, using leverage and system value rather than convenience.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- The better next automation target is:\n  - **`escalation_status` first**\n- Reasoning:\n  - `drift_note` is lower risk but mostly descriptive\n  - `escalation_status` directly upgrades the loop into a real decision surface\n  - the guardrails needed for escalation logic are already defined in V11k\n- Wrote priority-decision artifact: `/home/ubuntu/clawd/patches/v11v-next-automation-priority-drift-vs-escalation.spec.md`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis feels like the right call. I\u2019m not interested in polishing narration before the system can make the more important judgment. If we automate escalation first, the loop becomes materially smarter; if we automate drift-note first, it mostly just sounds nicer.\n\n**Decision:**\n- Prioritize automation of `escalation_status` before `drift_note`.\n- Leave `drift_note` manual until the escalation path is live.\n\n**Next:** On the next P2 heartbeat, define the exact comparison log",
